1 Introduction

      This is the part II of CITS4009 Introduction to Data Science assessment continuing from the part I, an exploratory data analysis. In this project, predictive models based on National Enrollment Dataset from year 2005 to 2017 using statistical classification methods, Naive Bayes, decision tree and K-nearest neighbour algroithms, are carried out to answer the question whether the enrollment (student) is with high ATAR (80 and above) or not. Moreover, cluster analysis using Hierarchical clustering and k-means algorithm are also conducted to find a similar enrollment patterns. The National Enrollment Dataset is distributed by the University of Western Australia as a part of the CITS4009 Introduction to Data Science assessment. The entire dataset spans across 13 years (2005 to 2017), covers 41 Australian institutions. With a total of 12896962 records, a stratified dataset with 1% records from each institution is then obtained to make the assessment more accessible. This dataset provides data on 128967 students with 46 attributes.

2 Statistical Classification

      Classification is the supervised learning techniques used for determining a set of categories a new observation belongs based on the known observations in a training set of data. Since, the National Enrollments data consists of many labeled categorical variables, classification method can be employed in order to predict a category a new student belongs to. In this project, Naive Bayes, Decision Trees and K-nearest neighbour algorithms were applied to build three predictive models to identify whether the enrollment (student) is with high ATAR (above 80) or not, and then evaluation of the models’ performance was conducted.

      In part I of the project, we have already tidied and cleaned the National Enrollment data. However, to be able to build a model to make predictions, a sampling is required in order to developing and refining a modeling process, and also validating an accuracy or a precision of the model. We usually do this by splitting the data into two set, a training set where we feed the model-building algorithm, and a test set which we feed into the resulting model to verify its accuracy. Further splitting of training data set into calibration set is also necessary in selecting combination of important features to be included in our model. With the use of R base functions and package dplyr, we are able to construct the training set, test set and calibration set of the National Enrollment data.

      The code chucks in the following sections were adapted from Chapter 5 and Chapter 6 of Practical Data Science with R (Zumel and Mount, 2014)

2.1 Model Validation

      In order to evaluate the model performance, we basically want to calculate one or two summary scores that tell us whether the model is effective or not. Then, to be able to interpret the summary scores, We have to set up the lower bound (lowest performance) and the upper bound (highest performance) for the model to calibrate against. It is a good idea to set up the boundary early on in the study, so that we could simultaneously evaluate the model performance as we move on to the actual model building process. The lower bound and the upper bound of the model performance are also known as the null model and the Bayes rate (saturated) model, respectively. Moreover, single-variable models are also built to give us a general idea of what a simple model can achieve, and thus we would like our predictive models to do better.

      With the construction of a confusion matrix, we can conveniently calculate many important evaluation score such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, etc. To specifically evaluate classification models, the most common measure we use is accuracy. However, we previously observed from the data exploratory section that there are much less proportion of enrollments with high ATAR, and thus accuracy would be inappropriate for an assessment of such a rare event. Another evaluation measure is a pair of precision and recall scores, which also known as a measure of confirmation and a measure of utility, respectively. These two scores are considered to be a good measures to discuss and as well interpret. Moreover, F1 score can be determined from the combination of precision and recall, where the classifier that improves precision or recall by sacrificing a lot of the complementary measure will have a lower F1. In addition, we are able to compute sensitivity (recall or true positive rate) and specificity (true negative rate), which are the favourable measures of effect, especially in the health science area. Plotting the true positive rate against the false positive rate at various threshold settings, also known as the receiver operating characteristic curve (ROC curve), and calculate the area under the curve (AUC) is another method which is used to explore possible project goal trade-offs. In this project, I decided to employ sensitivity, specificity score and ROC analysis for classification model evaluation.

      First, let’s split the National Enrollment data into training and test set. Using runif() function for the entire observations to generate random numbers from uniform distribution for each observation, and then drawn out 10 percent of the observation by giving condition that the generated number must be greater than \(0.9\), we can effectively split the original data into two set, the training set and test set. The training set should consist of roughly 90% of the observations, while the test set should consist of roughly 10% of the observations. A function dim() can be used to check whether our codes work as we expected or not.

set.seed(729375)
enrol2$rgroup <- runif(dim(enrol2)[1])
dTrainAll <- subset(enrol2, enrol2$rgroup <= 0.9)
dTest <- subset(enrol2, enrol2$rgroup > 0.9)
dim(dTrainAll)[1]/dim(enrol2)[1]
[1] 0.8997119
dim(dTest)[1]/dim(enrol2)[1]
[1] 0.1002881

2.1.1 The Null Model

      The null model is basically a constant value which identify the lower-bound of the desired performance, which we want our final model to outperform. The two most common null model choices are a model that is returning the same answer for all situation or a model that is independent. Since we are working on a categorical problem, the most suitable null model in this case would constantly returns the most popular category. The proportion of high ATAR enrollments is calculated to determine the most common category.

percent(round(sum(ifelse(enrol2$High_ATAR == 1,1,0))/dim(enrol2)[[1]],4))
[1] "9%"

      There is a considerably low proportion of high ATAR enrollments, which suggests that our null model should always identify every enrollment as non-high/missing ATAR. Theoretically, null classifiers would return a zero score on either sensitivity or specificity. Let’s check these evaluation scores by construct the confusion matrix.

dTest$predNull <- -1
cM <- table(truth = factor(dTest$High_ATAR), prediction = factor(dTest$predNull, level = c(-1,1)));cM
     prediction
truth    -1     1
   -1 11006     0
   1   1074     0
rec <- cM[2,2]/(cM[2,2]+cM[2,1])
tnr <- cM[1,1]/(cM[1,1]+cM[1,2])
print(sprintf("Null model recall (sensitivity): %4.3f", rec))
[1] "Null model recall (sensitivity): 0.000"
print(sprintf("Null model specificity (tnr): %4.3f", tnr))
[1] "Null model specificity (tnr): 1.000"

      Just a reminder that we previously set 1 to represent enrollments with high ATAR and -1 otherwise. Here, from the confusion matrix, we are able to calculate precision, sensitivity and specificity as shown above. It is obvious that The sensitivity in this case returns 0, while the specificity returns 1. From this point, we can also plot the ROC curve of the null model and determine its AUC.

plot(performance(prediction(dTest$predNull, dTest$High_ATAR), "tpr", "fpr"),
     main = "Null model ROC curve") %>% abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)

      The red dashed lines represents a line of no-discrimination or random guesses. The ROC curve which perform no better than random guesses would return the same pattern as this dashed line. If we calculate the area under this ROC curve, it would return \(0.5\). Thus, we can use the AUC of \(0.5\) as our lower-bound AUC for model evaluation.

2.1.2 Single-variable Models

      Now, the single-variable models are built to help organize the training data into a number of subsets indexed by the predictive variable and then store a summary of the distribution of outcome as their future prediction. The best single-variable model is also useful to compare any complicated model against. If the complicated model does not outperform the best single-variable model, then that model cannot be justified.

  1. Identifying outcome and creating variable object (vars)

      In this project, we want to predict the enrollment whether the average ATAR is high (above 80) or not. Hence, the object outcome and pos were assigned with the value representing our outcome of interest. A High_ATAR column was created in the Cleaning Data section having ATAR above 80 classified as ‘1’ and others classified as ‘-1’. The variable object, vars, consists of name of attributes excluding the outcome column, columns associated with the outcome and uniformly distributed random numbers column.

outcome <- "High_ATAR"
pos <- "1"
vars <- setdiff(colnames(dTrainAll), c(outcome, "rgroup", "atar_fixed", "ATAR_Group"))
  1. Identifying categorical variables and numerical variables in the data frame and further splitting training data into training and calibration set.

      Since categorical and numerical variables required different techniques to deal with, extracting the name of all the variables and put them in different objects based on their class for later analysis is useful. Also, the training set of data was divided further into the calibration set for features selection.

catVars <- vars[sapply(dTrainAll[, vars], class) %in% c('factor', 'character')]
numericVars <- vars[sapply(dTrainAll[, vars], class) %in% c('numeric', 'integer')]

useForCal <- rbinom(n = dim(dTrainAll)[[1]], size = 1, prob = 0.1) > 0
dCal <- subset(dTrainAll, useForCal)
dTrain <- subset(dTrainAll, !useForCal)
  1. Building single-variable models for all categorical variables

      A single-variable model is useful in selecting potential classifiers. It is essentially a model building method using one variable at a time, which is pretty exasperating for dataset with many variables. Hence, with the use of function() and for loop, we are able to build a single-categorical variable models to all variables in our dataset using the code chunk below.

  • Function to repeat model building
mkPredC <- function(outCol, varCol, appCol) {
  pPos <- sum(outCol == pos)/length(outCol)
  naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]))
  pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
  vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol), varCol)
  pPosWv <- (vTab[pos,] + 1.0e-3 * pPos)/(colSums(vTab) + 1.0e-3)
  pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
  pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
  pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
  pred
}
  • Applying single-categorical variable models to all of our datasets
for(v in catVars) {
  pi <- paste('pred', v, sep = '')
  dTrain[, pi] <- mkPredC(dTrain[, outcome], dTrain[, v], dTrain[, v])
  dCal[, pi] <- mkPredC(dTrain[, outcome], dTrain[, v], dCal[, v])
  dTest[, pi] <- mkPredC(dTrain[, outcome], dTrain[, v], dTest[, v])
}

      An area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC of ROC curve) was computed to assess classifiers performance and identify over-fitting problem. The closer to 1 the AUC is, the better the classifier. Since the National Enrollment data consists of many variables, with the use of function() and for loop, we can work out the area under the ROC curve for each variables for both training set and calibration set.

calcAUC <- function(predcol, outcol) {
  perf <- performance(prediction(predcol, outcol == pos), 'auc')
  as.numeric(perf@y.values)
}

for(v in catVars) {
  pi <- paste('pred', v, sep='')
  aucTrain <- calcAUC(dTrain[, pi], dTrain[, outcome])
  if(aucTrain >= 0.8) {
    aucCal <- calcAUC(dCal[, pi], dCal[, outcome])
    print(sprintf("%s, trainAUC: %4.3f calibrationAUC: %4.3f", pi, aucTrain, aucCal))
  }
}
[1] "predage, trainAUC: 0.840 calibrationAUC: 0.849"
[1] "predbasis_for_admission, trainAUC: 0.885 calibrationAUC: 0.902"
[1] "predhighest_ed_attainment, trainAUC: 0.895 calibrationAUC: 0.903"

      Using the training AUC threshold of \(0.8\), only the classifiers in training set with AUC greater than or equal to 0.8 were printed. The AUC is essentially the probability that a classifier will rank a randomly chosen positive instance higher than a randomly chosen negative one (“Receiver operating_characteristic”, n.d.). From above output, the classifiers identify by the code satisfied by the threshold are predage, predbasis_for_admission and predhighest_ed_attainment, while predhighest_ed_attainment seems to have the highest AUCs. Also, the training AUC of these classifiers are approximately close to their calibration AUCs, which indicates that the variables are not subject to over-fitting.

      Below is the ROC curve illustrating relative trade-offs between true positive and false positive rates of predage, predbasis_for_admission and predhighest_ed_attainment, respectively. The red dashed lines represents a line of no-discrimination or random guess. An ROC curve above the no-discrimination line indicates better prediction than random guessing. The closer the curve to the top left corner of the plot, the better the prediction.

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
plot(performance(prediction(dTest[, "predage"], dTest[, outcome]), "tpr", "fpr"),
     main = "Age") %>% abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)
plot(performance(prediction(dTest[, "predbasis_for_admission"], dTest[, outcome]), "tpr", "fpr"),
     main = "Basis for Admission") %>% abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)
plot(performance(prediction(dTest[, "predhighest_ed_attainment"], dTest[, outcome]), "tpr", "fpr"),
     main = "Highest Education Attainment") %>% abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)

      As expected, all the ROC curves shows a relatively high true positive rate with respect to the false positive rate. The ROC curve of the single-variable model using highest_ed_attainment seems to be the one that is closest the top left corner of the plot. Hence, we can conclude that our best single-variable model to predict enrollment with high ATAR is predhighest_ed_attainment with AUC of 0.89.

  1. Converting numeric variables into categorical

      This can be done by binning numeric variable into a number of ranges. There is only one numeric variable in our data set which is atar_fixed. However, since our outcome variable High_ATAR is essentially derived from the atar_fixed column, then it was dropped from our investigation from the very beginning due to redundancy problem. Hence, we do not have to deal with numeric variable in this case.

  1. 100-fold Cross-validation

      Recall the AUC of classifiers in both training and calibration set we obtained from step 5, training AUC is fairly close to calibration AUC which means that our training estimate tends to be good and not over-fit. To ensure that we were not over-fitting the model, repeated cross-validation was conducted on the single-variable model based on variable Highest_ed_attainment.

fCross <- function() {
  useForCalRep <- rbinom(n = dim(dTrainAll)[[1]], size = 1,prob = 0.1) > 0
  predRep <- mkPredC(dTrainAll[!useForCalRep, outcome],
                     dTrainAll[!useForCalRep, var],
                     dTrainAll[useForCalRep, var])
  calcAUC(predRep, dTrainAll[useForCalRep, outcome])
}

var <- "highest_ed_attainment"

aucs <- replicate(100, fCross())

print(sprintf("%s, MeanAUC: %4.3f sdAUC: %4.3f", var, mean(aucs), sd(aucs)))
[1] "highest_ed_attainment, MeanAUC: 0.896 sdAUC: 0.004"

      The original training AUC of highest_ed_attainment variable of \(0.895\) is very close to the 100-fold replicated estimate of mean AUC of \(0.896\) with a relatively small standard error of \(0.004\). Hence, our original estimated AUC is good enough.

      In conclusion, the most promising variable is highest_ed_attainment, which has training AUC of 0.895 and calibration AUC of 0.903. Hence, it is apparently much better than random guesses or our null model. In the following sections, we will compare the best single-variable model’s AUCs with other complicated models to decide whether which model is the best.

2.1.3 The Bayes Rate Model

      The Bayes rate or error rate of a saturated model essentially tells us what high performance looks like. It is an ideal model with no bias or variance terms and can be described as the limit on prediction accuracy due to unexplained variance. Unfortunately, determining the exact Bayes rate is not always feasible, because if we are able to find it, our job would already be done. The Bayes rate model, however, can be estimated by building a look-up table for all possible variable combination or using a nearest-neighbour classifier. However, the only problem arise for the Bayes rate model using a look-up table is when there are multiple examples with the exact same set of known facts but different outcome. For example, there are five female domestic students who studied data sciences at UWA in 2017. Assuming that all other characteristics are the same, only one of them obtained a substantially high ATAR. Let’s put this example into a table for a better understanding.

t <- as.table(matrix(data = c("female", "female", "female", "female", "female",
                              TRUE, TRUE, TRUE, TRUE, TRUE,
                              "DataSci", "DataSci", "DataSci", "DataSci", "DataSci",
                              "UWA", "UWA", "UWA", "UWA", "UWA", 
                              "2017", "2017", "2017", "2017", "2017",
                              FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE,
                              FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE),
                     nrow = 5, ncol = 7))
rownames(t) <- c(1:5)
colnames(t) <- c("gender", "domestic", "course", "uni", "year", "high ATAR", "Bayes")
print(t)
  gender domestic course  uni year high ATAR Bayes
1 female TRUE     DataSci UWA 2017 FALSE     FALSE
2 female TRUE     DataSci UWA 2017 FALSE     FALSE
3 female TRUE     DataSci UWA 2017 FALSE     FALSE
4 female TRUE     DataSci UWA 2017 TRUE      FALSE
5 female TRUE     DataSci UWA 2017 FALSE     FALSE

      Now, we can see that there’s a disagreement in the high ATAR outcomes where all other features are the same. The Bayes rate model, in this example, will undoubtedly predict that the student number 4 did not obtain a high ATAR due to the fact that all other students with the same characteristics did not. From here, we can conclude that the highest performance we can get for this example is an accuracy of \(4/5 = 80\) percent.

rm(t)

      For our dataset, it is actually very difficult to do the same thing, since there are many feature values and each feature also has a large number of levels. Hence, it probably be more appropriate to use the nearest-neighbour classifier as an estimation of the Bayes rate. We will discuss about the nearest neighbour algorithm in section 2.4 K-nearest Neighbour Method.

2.2 Naive Bayes

      Once, we are done building single-variable models, then we can move on to building models using many variable. First, Naive Bayes is a memorization method which is useful for data with many categorical input variables with a very large number of possible values. The method is known to be a good first attempt at solving product categorical problem. Hence, it can be used to identify whether the enrollment is with high ATAR (above 80) or not. In this section, naiveBayes() function from e1071 packages was applied to determine the conditional posterior probability of a categorical class variable given independent predictor variables using the famous Bayes rule. Then, the obtained Naive Bayes model (nbmodel) was applied to make a prediction using prediction() function. Lastly, the AUCs of training set, test set and calibration set were then calculated to evaluate the Naive Bayes model performance.

ff <- paste('as.factor(', outcome, '>0) ~ ', 
            paste(catVars, collapse = ' + '), sep = '')
nbmodel <- naiveBayes(as.formula(ff), data = dCal)
dTrain$nbpred <- predict(nbmodel, newdata = dTrain, type= 'raw')[, 'TRUE']
dCal$nbpred <- predict(nbmodel, newdata = dCal, type='raw')[, 'TRUE']
dTest$nbpred <- predict(nbmodel,newdata = dTest, type='raw')[, 'TRUE']

calcAUC(dTrain$nbpred, dTrain[, outcome])
[1] 0.9402017
calcAUC(dCal$nbpred, dCal[, outcome])
[1] 0.9500899
calcAUC(dTest$nbpred, dTest[, outcome])
[1] 0.9432486

      The area under the ROC curves (AUCs) in this case is a measure of prediction quality or performance of the model. The AUCs above our lower bound of 0.5 means that the model predictive performance is better than random guesses, while the AUCs of 1.0 means the perfect classifiers. The Naive Bayes model returns all the AUCS of about 0.94 which are very close to 1 and close to each other. Recall that our best single-variable model returns the AUC of 0.89. This suggests that Naive Bayes model performs better than the single-variable model and is a very good classifier without over-fitting problem presented. Below are the corresponding ROC curves of the AUCs we calculated above.

plot(performance(prediction(dTest$nbpred, dTest[, outcome]), "tpr", "fpr"),
     main = "Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve") %>% abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)

2.3 Decision Trees using Selected Features

      Decision tree is a classification method which is useful when there’s an ‘if-then’ relationship between input variables and the outcome, and when the input variables have an ‘AND’ relationship between each other. The process involves splitting the training data into pieces (data cuts) and apply a simple memorized constant on each piece. The best data cuts based on many criteria are then chosen to fit a decision tree model.

      Firstly, a variable selection based on Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) is conducted. This preselecting process is done to help control a possible source of noise and over-fitting. We can do that by using a knowledge of log likelihood, deviance and Akaike Information Criterion. The AIC is particularly useful for comparing models with different measures of complexity and variable with different number of levels. As mentioned before, we will use calibration set for variables selecting.

logLikelyhood <- function(outCol, predCol) {
  sum(ifelse(outCol == pos, log(predCol), log(1 - predCol)))
}

selVars <- c()
minStep <- 5
baseRateCheck <- logLikelyhood(dCal[, outcome],
                               sum(dCal[, outcome] == pos)/length(dCal[, outcome]))
for(v in catVars) {
  pi <- paste('pred', v, sep = '')
  liCheck <- 2*((logLikelyhood(dCal[, outcome], dCal[, pi]) - baseRateCheck))
  
  if(liCheck > minStep) {
    print(sprintf("%s, calibrationScore: %g", pi, liCheck))
    selVars <- c(selVars, pi)
  }
}

      There are 26 variables out of 33 variables which were preselected based on the AIC score as shown in the above list. Next, with the use of rpart() function from rpart package, we are able to build a decision tree model of High ATAR variable below.

f <- paste(outcome, '>0 ~ ', paste(selVars, collapse = ' + '), sep = '')
tmodel <- rpart(f, data = dTrain, 
                control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001, 
                                        minsplit = 1000, 
                                        minbucket = 1000, 
                                        maxdepth = 3))
print(tmodel)

The condition on each parent node must be met to move to the corresponding child node. The three numbers after the condition of each node are the number of training items that navigated to the node, the deviance measuring how much uncertainty remains at a given node, and the fraction of items that were in the positive class at the node, respectively.       All the AUCs are above 0.5 and 0.89 and essentially close to 1 which indicates that the decision tree model performs better than the null model and the single-variable model. However, the decision tree’s AUC is a bit less than that of Naive Bayes. So, this suggests that the Naive Bayes model perform better.

2.4 K-nearest Neighbour Method

      The K-nearest neighbour classification method is one of the most convenient classification method to carry out in R. It is essentially the method that scores an example by finding the \(k\) training examples nearest to the example and then taking the average outcomes as the score. Then, the question is how many \(k\) we would want to build a sensible model? Since the probability of high ATAR is considerably low (about 8.7%), choosing a low number of \(k\) for kNN will underestimate all the useful range of probabilities. Hence, for the rare event like this, a large \(k\) value is usually employed. The basic rule of thumb is that we would want to see 10 positive example in each of the neighbourhood. So, we would want \(k\) around \(10/0.087 \approx 115\) or greater. In this section, the 200 nearest (in Euclidean distance) training set vectors are found, and the classification is decided by majority vote with ties broken at random.

      As we discussed in section 2.1.3 The Bayes Rate Model, the nearest-neighbour classifier is also a good estimator of Bayes rate for the National Enrollment dataset.

kNN method is conducted using knn() function from package class. Again, the area under the ROC curve are calculated

nK <- 200
knnTrain <- dCal[, selVars]
knnCl <- dCal[, outcome] == pos
knnPred <- function(df) {
    knnDecision <- knn(knnTrain, df, knnCl, k = nK, prob = T)
    ifelse(knnDecision == TRUE, attributes(knnDecision)$prob, 1-(attributes(knnDecision)$prob))
}

print(calcAUC(knnPred(dTrain[, selVars]), dTrain[, outcome]))
[1] 0.9423186
print(calcAUC(knnPred(dCal[, selVars]) ,dCal[, outcome]))
[1] 0.9532982
print(calcAUC(knnPred(dTest[, selVars]), dTest[, outcome]))
[1] 0.9450924

      All the AUCs are very close to one which indicates a good separation performance of a model. Also, the AUCs of kNN model are all higher than the null model, the single variable model, the decision tree model, and the Naive Bayes Model. Hence, we can conclude that the classification model based on K-nearest neighbour method is essentially the best model to predict the enrollments with high ATAR, and thus our best Bayes rate estimate.

plotROC <- function(predcol,outcol) {
   perf <- performance(prediction(predcol, outcol == pos), "tpr", "fpr")
   pf <- data.frame(FalsePositiveRate = perf@x.values[[1]],
                    TruePositiveRate = perf@y.values[[1]])
ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = pf, aes(x = FalsePositiveRate, y = TruePositiveRate)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = c(0,1), y = c(0,1)), colour = "red") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5))
}
print(plotROC(knnPred(dTest[, selVars]), dTest[, outcome]))

      The trade-off between the sensitivity (TPR) and specificity (FPR) as shown by the ROC curve above suggests a relatively high TPR with respect to FPR, which is a good sign. The ROC curve above the red diagonal line also indicates a better performance than random guesses.

      Moreover, to visualise the performance of our 200-nearest neighbour model, a density plot and a double density plot are created as shown below:

dCal$kpred <- knnPred(dCal[, selVars])

ggplot(dCal) +
  geom_density(aes(x = kpred, colour = as.factor(High_ATAR),
                   linetype = as.factor(High_ATAR)), size = 1) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "200-nearest neighbour Performance Density Plot") +
  scale_colour_discrete(name = "High ATAR",
                        breaks = c("-1", "1"),
                        labels = c("Not High/Missing ATAR", "High ATAR")) +
  scale_linetype_discrete(name = "High ATAR",
                        breaks = c("-1", "1"),
                        labels = c("Not High/Missing ATAR", "High ATAR")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5))

      The above double density plot shows the conditional distribution of of kNN model prediction (kpred) for High ATAR enrollments (the blue dashed-line density plot) and the distribution of kpred for non-high ATAR enrollments (the red solid-line density plot. A fairly clear separation between the double density plot is expected for a good kNN model. The double density plot above suggests that a relatively low value of kpred are rather common for non-high ATAR enrollments and very rare for high ATAR enrollments. Hence, we can conclude that a low value of kpred is a good evidence that the enrollments is with non-high or missing ATAR.

3 Clustering

      Clustering is an unsupervised methods which is used to discover unknown relationships in the data. Unlike the supervised or memorization methods in the previous section, there is no obvious outcome we try to predict; instead we are trying to uncover some obscure patterns we had not previously suspected. There are two clustering approaches mentioned in the text book, Hierarchical clustering and k-means clustering algorithms. In the hierarchical clustering method, clusters have a standard parent-child relationship or a tree-based structure where similar clusters are combined together and continue to combine until all objects are in the same cluster, whereas K-means clustering approach tries to group similar observations in the same cluster. K-means clustering is also known to be effective for finding clusters in quantitative data.

      The expectation of this project is to group the enrollments into clusters such that every enrollment in the same cluster is more similar to one another than it is to to enrollments in other clusters. Hence, we are able to find groups of students with similar enrollment patterns.

      The code in the following section was adapted from Chapter 8 of Practical Data Science with R (Zumel and Mount, 2014).

3.1 Data Preparation

      Firstly, we will choose or compute a set of feature variables to apply the clustering algorithm. In this section, we obtained the numerical aggregations for each institution type each broad field of study each enrollment year, the average age, the proportion of high ATAR students, the proportion of male students, the number of international students, the number of home-state students and the number of inter-state students. Since, there’s a substantially high proportion of enrollments with missing ATAR due to the students did not commence an undergraduate course, did not complete Australian Year 12, or their ATAR score is just simply not available, I decided to limit the investigation only for undergraduate students with ATAR, so that we can average the ATAR score without bias.

  • Data Preparation
# Converting age range to numeric (assume age distribution is left skewed)
enrol2$age_num <- ifelse(enrol2$age == "16 and under", 16, # Assume mode is 16
                  ifelse(enrol2$age == "30 to 39", mean(30:39),
                  ifelse(enrol2$age == "40 to 49", mean(40:49),
                  ifelse(enrol2$age == "50 to 59", mean(50:59),
                  ifelse(enrol2$age == "60 and over", 60, # Assume mode is 60
                         as.character(enrol2$age))))))
enrol2$age_num <- as.numeric(enrol2$age_num)

# International students
enrol2$International <- ifelse(enrol2$Australian_Region_fixed == "International", 1, 0)

# home-state students
enrol2$HomeState <- ifelse(enrol2$Australian_Region_fixed == "HomeState", 1, 0)

# inter-state students
enrol2$InterState <- ifelse(enrol2$Australian_Region_fixed == "InterState", 1, 0)

# Male students
enrol2$Male <- ifelse(enrol2$gender == "Males", 1, 0)
  • Numerical aggregations

      With the use of data transformation package dplyr and its data handling function (pipe), we are able to obtain the numerical aggregation of the average age, the average ATAR score, proportion of male students, number of international enrollments, number of homestate enrollments and the number of interstate enrollments grouped by enrollment year, institution type and broad field of education type.

enrol3 <- enrol2 %>%
  subset(!is.na(atar_fixed)) %>%
  group_by(Year, Institution_Type, broad_foe) %>%
  summarise(avgAge = mean(age_num, na.rm = TRUE),
            avgATAR = mean(atar_fixed, na.rm = TRUE),
            propMale = mean(Male),
            noInter = sum(International),
            noHomeState = sum(HomeState),
            noInterState = sum(InterState)) %>%
  transform(Year = as.character(Year),
            Institution_Type = as.character(Institution_Type),
            broad_foe = as.character(broad_foe)) %>%
  unite(Yr_InsType_Foe, Year, Institution_Type, broad_foe,
        sep = " ", remove = TRUE) %>%
  transform(Yr_InsType_Foe = as.factor(Yr_InsType_Foe))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year', 'Institution_Type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
head(enrol3)
  • Standardized data

      To avoid clustering with inconsistent units and to take into account the degree of difference in each attributes, a data transformation process is required before carry out the analysis. In order to make the clustering more coordinate-free, we usually standardize all the columns to have a mean value of 0 and a standard deviation of 1 (z-normalization). Once the data is scaled, now the variables can be comparable without bias. This can be done by passing the function scale to the numeric attributes, namely avgAge, avgATAR, propMale, noInter, noHomeState and noInterState.

vars.to.use <- colnames(enrol3)[-1]
pmatrix <- scale(enrol3[, vars.to.use])
pcenter <- attr(pmatrix, "scaled:center")
pscale <- attr(pmatrix, "scaled:scale")
  • Measuring distance

      In order to group observations into clusters, we need to find similarity and dissimilarity between data points. This can be done by measuring distance between each points, where points in a cluster are closer to each other than they are to the points in other clusters. There are essentially four most commons approaches to determine distance and dissimilarity, namely Euclidean distance, Hamming distance, Manhattan distance and Cosine similarity. Since, our new dataset enrol3 consists of numeric (quantitative) values, the Euclidean distance between data points were used to determine similarity and dissimilarity of the observations. Below, the function dist is applied to our scaled data to calculate the distance matrix using the Euclidean distance method.

d <- dist(pmatrix, method = "euclidean")

3.2 Hierarchical Clustering

      By passing the function hclust to the distance matrix using Ward’s method, we are able to plot a cluster dendogram. The Ward’s method basically refers to an iterative merge of individual data point into clusters so as to minimize the total within sum of squares (WSS) of the clustering. The dendogram is essentially a tree representing the nested clusters as shown below.

pfit <- hclust(d, method = "ward.D")
plot(pfit, labels = FALSE)
rect.hclust(pfit, k = 2, border = 3:4)
rect.hclust(pfit, k = 4, border = c(3,3,4,4))

      The cluster dendogram above suggests that there should be around 2 or 4 clusters. Here, the function rect.hclust was used to draw rectangles around the branch of a dendrogram highlighting the corresponding clusters for \(k = 2\) and \(k = 4\). Intuitively, I would choose \(k = 2\) because it is possible that the clusters correspond to Go8 and non-Go8 university. We can investigate clustering with different number of clusters by using a function cutree to extract the members of each cluster from the hclust object, and then we plot the clusters by projecting them on the first two principal component.

  • \(k = 2\)
groupsk2 <- cutree(pfit, k = 2)
print_clusters <- function(labels, k) {
  for(i in 1:k) {
    print(paste("cluster", i))
    print(enrol3[labels == i,
                  c("Yr_InsType_Foe", "avgAge",
                    "avgATAR", "propMale","noInter",
                    "noHomeState", "noInterState")])
  }
}
print_clusters(groupsk2, 2)
[1] "cluster 1"
[1] "cluster 2"

      Unfortunately, the value of \(k = 2\) does not give us the clusters correspond to Go8 and non-Go8 institutions. However, the observations in each cluster tend to be grouped with a certain logic. With \(k=2\), the average age and the average ATAR score of both clusters are not that much different. The observations from cluster 1 seems to have higher number of international, homestate and interstate enrollments, and also have higher proportion of male students.

  • \(k = 4\)
groupsk4 <- cutree(pfit, k = 4)
print_clusters(groupsk4, 4)
[1] "cluster 1"
[1] "cluster 2"
[1] "cluster 3"
[1] "cluster 4"

      Now with the value of \(k = 4\), it is even more difficult to find a logic behind the clustering process this time when there are many observations in the data. Again, the average age of all clusters are not that much different. The average ATAR of cluster 3 seems to be higher than other clusters, while the average ATAR of cluster 4 seems to be lower than others. Cluster 1 seems to have higher proportion of male students than the other clusters with substantially lower number of international, homestate and interstate enrollments. Cluster 2 also consists less number of international, homestate and interstate enrollments than others with considerably low proportion of male students. Cluster 4 on the other hand, have substantially higher number of international, homestate and interstate enrollments than cluster 2 with about the same proportion of male students.

      Interpreting the clusters like this many times would be exasperating. In the next section we will examine these clusters in a more effective way. But before we move on to the next section, let’s visualise the clusters for \(k = 2\) and \(k = 4\) to get the general idea of what they look like. Since our data consists of many variables, we make use of the principal components analysis to capture as much of the variation of the data in two dimensional spaces. In the code chunk below, we projected the clusters on the first two principal components of the data by using the function prcomp(), and then we plot the clusters using function ggplot().

  • Visualising Clusters
princ <- prcomp(pmatrix)
nComp <- 2
project <- as.data.frame(predict(princ, newdata = pmatrix))[, 1:nComp]
project.plusk2 <- cbind(as.data.frame(project), cluster = as.factor(groupsk2),
                      Yr_InsType_Foe = enrol3$Yr_InsType_Foe)
hk2 <- do.call(rbind, lapply(unique(groupsk2),
                           function(c) {
                             f <- subset(project.plusk2, cluster == c);
                             f[chull(f),]
                           }
                           )
             )

p1 <- ggplot(project.plusk2, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = cluster), show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_polygon(data = hk2, aes(group = cluster, fill = as.factor(cluster)),
               alpha = 0.4, linetype = 0) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5)) +
  labs(fill = "Cluster", title = "k = 2")

project.plusk4 <- cbind(as.data.frame(project), cluster = as.factor(groupsk4),
                      Yr_InsType_Foe = enrol3$Yr_InsType_Foe)
hk4 <- do.call(rbind, lapply(unique(groupsk4),
                           function(c) {
                             f <- subset(project.plusk4, cluster == c);
                             f[chull(f),]
                           }
                           )
             )

p2 <- ggplot(project.plusk4, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = cluster), show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_polygon(data = hk4, aes(group = cluster, fill = as.factor(cluster)),
               alpha = 0.4, linetype = 0) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = .5)) +
  labs(fill = "Cluster", title = "k = 4")

grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=2)

rm(p1,p2)

      For \(k = 2\), the clusters are not that well-separated. For \(k = 4\), cluster 1 and cluster 3 are quite well-separated, while cluster 2 and cluster 4 completely overlap. However, an important question is that whether a given cluster is “real” and representing the true structures or not. To asses whether this is the case and the cluster does hold up plausible variations in the dataset, the function clusterboot() from fpc package was applied to our scaled data to evaluate the stability of a given cluster. The clusterboot() algorithms carries out clusterwise cluster stability assessment by resampling and then compute the Jaccard coefficient representing the similarities of the original clusters to the most similar clusters in the resampled data. The cluster stability is then obtained from the mean value of the Jaccard coefficient. The stability of less than 0.6 is considered as unstable. The values between 0.6 and 0.75 indicate the patterns are discovered but with low certainty. Lastly, the stability value of greater than 0.85 is considered as highly stable and possibly be the real clusters.

      The clusterboot() results when \(k=4\) show that both cluster 3 and 4 are quite stable. Cluster 1 and 2, on the other hand, are unstable with stability value less than 0.6.

      One major drawback is that clusterboot assumes that we know the number of clusters beforehand, whether by looking at the cluster dendogram or simply trusting our instincts. However, intuitively guessing the number of clusters does work for some dataset but not very effective with our National Enrollment data. Luckily, we are able to effectively determine the number of clusters by using the knowledge of the total within sum of squares (WSS) and the Callinski-Harabasz index (CH).

  • Total within sum of squares (WSS)

      The within sum of squares is essentially the average squared distance of each point in the cluster from its centroid (mean of all the points in the cluster), while the total within sum of squares is basically the sum of the within sum of squares of all the clusters. One way to determine the number of clusters, \(k\), is to calculate WSS for different values of \(k\) and look for an elbow in the curve. The code chunk below create three functions which are used to calculate the total WSS value. The first function sqr_edist calculate a squared distance between vector \(x\) and \(y\). The wss.cluster function calculate the within sum of squares of a single cluster. Lastly, the wss.total function calculate the total WSS from a set of data points and cluster labels.

sqr_edist <- function(x, y) {
  sum((x - y)^2)
}

wss.cluster <- function(clustermat) {
  c0 <- apply(clustermat, 2, FUN = mean)
  sum(apply(clustermat, 1, FUN = function(row){sqr_edist(row, c0)}))
}

wss.total <- function(dmatrix, labels) {
  wsstot <- 0
  k <- length(unique(labels))
  for(i in 1:k){
    wsstot <- wsstot + wss.cluster(subset(dmatrix, labels == i))
  }
  wsstot
}
  • Calinski-Harabasz index

      The Calinski-Harabasz index or CH index is essentially the ratio of the between-cluster variance determined from the variance of all the cluster centroids from the dataset’s grand centroid to the average WSS of the clusters in the clustering, which can be defined as \(ch = \frac{B}{W}\) where \(B\) represents the between-cluster variance and \(W\) indicates the within-cluster variance. Moreover, the between-cluster variance and the within-cluster variance can be calculated by \(B = \frac{BSS(k)}{k-1} = TSS - WSS(k)\) and \(W = \frac{WSS(k)}{n-k}\), respectively. The ratio of B to W should theoretically maximized at the optimal number of cluster \(k\) and thus the elbow curve.

      Firstly, we need to calculate the total sum of squares (TSS) by creating the function totss as in the code chunk below. Then, the function ch_criterion is used to calculate the CH index for a number of clusters from 1 to kmax, which in this case we choose the kmax equal to 10.

totss <- function(dmatrix) {
  grandmean <- apply(dmatrix, 2, FUN=mean)
  sum(apply(dmatrix, 1, 
            FUN=function(row){
              sqr_edist(row, grandmean)
              }
            )
      )
}

ch_criterion <- function(dmatrix, kmax, method = "kmeans") {
  if(!(method %in% c("kmeans", "hclust"))){ 
    stop("method must be one of c('kmeans', 'hclust')")
  }
  npts <- dim(dmatrix)[1] # number of rows.
  totss <- totss(dmatrix)
  wss <- numeric(kmax)
  crit <- numeric(kmax)
  wss[1] <- (npts - 1) * sum(apply(dmatrix, 2, var))
  for(k in 2:kmax) {
    if(method == "kmeans") {
      clustering <- kmeans(dmatrix, k, nstart = 10, iter.max = 100)
      wss[k] <- clustering$tot.withinss
    }else { # hclust
      d <- dist(dmatrix, method = "euclidean")
      pfit <- hclust(d, method = "ward.D")
      labels <- cutree(pfit, k = k)
      wss[k] <- wss.total(dmatrix, labels)
    }
  }
  bss <- totss - wss
  crit.num <- bss/(0:(kmax - 1))
  crit.denom <- wss/(npts - 1:kmax)
  list(crit = crit.num/crit.denom, wss = wss, totss = totss)
}

      To efficiently calculate and compare the WSS and CH index for the National Enrollment data, we can make use of visualisation.

clustcrit <- ch_criterion(pmatrix, 10, method = "hclust")
critframe <- data.frame(k = 1:10, ch = scale(clustcrit$crit), wss = scale(clustcrit$wss))
critframe <- melt(critframe, id.vars = c("k"), variable.name = "measure", value.name = "score")

ggplot(critframe, aes(x = k, y = score, colour = measure)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = measure)) + 
  geom_line(aes(linetype = measure)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:10, labels = 1:10) +
  theme_bw()

      It is obvious that the CH criterion is maximized at \(k = 2\) with another local maximum at \(k = 4\). The WSS plot on the other hand is quite difficult to determine the elbow. Nevertheless, we can say that there is a slight elbow at \(k = 2\) and \(k = 4\) for the WSS criterion also. Hence, both indices seem to suggest that there are 2 or 4 clusters, which matches with our preliminary investigation carried out at the beginning of this section.

3.3 K-means Clustering

      Since our data is quantitative, K-means clustering is known to be another effective way to carry out the clustering process. It is also a much quicker and simpler clustering method compare to the hierarchical clustering we did in the previous section. However, its drawback is that we must choose the number of clusters \(k\) in advance. Firstly, we start by passing the function kmeans to our scaled data with the chosen number of \(k\). Here, we chose the number of \(k = 2\) with 100 random start and 100 maximum iterations per run.

      Again, by passing the function summary to our kmeans output, we can see that kmeans essentially returns all the sum of squares measures. The centers component in this case is a matrix representing the centroids of the clusters.

pclusters <- kmeans(pmatrix, kbest.p, nstart = 100, iter.max = 100)
summary(pclusters)
             Length Class  Mode

centers       12    -none- numeric

withinss       2    -none- numeric
tot.withinss   1    -none- numeric
betweenss      1    -none- numeric
size           2    -none- numeric

ifault         1    -none- numeric

      Now, let’s extract the clusters found by kmeans with \(k=2\).

groups <- pclusters$cluster
print_clusters(groups, kbest.p)
[1] "cluster 1"
[1] "cluster 2"

      Interestingly, hclust and kmeans do not return the same clustering for \(k=2\). With about the same average age, average ATAR and proportion of male in both clusters, the number of international enrollments, the number of homestate enrollments and the number of interstate enrollment of cluster 1 seems to be substantially higher than cluster 2.

      As an alternative of ggplot, we can also visualise clusters found by k-means clustering with the function cusplot from the package cluster as shown below. The following code chunk was adapted from Manuel Ramon’s answer to the question “How to produce a pretty plot of the results of k-means cluster analysis?” on stackexchange.com.

clusplot(pmatrix, pclusters$cluster, color = TRUE, shade = TRUE, labels = 1, lines = 0)

      Rather than guessing what the number of clusters or \(k\) is, there is a much faster and more convenient way of determining the best possible value for \(k\). By using the function kmeansruns available in the fpc package, we are able to pick the best \(k\) based on the Calinski-Harabasz index (ch) or the average silhouette width (asw).

clustering.ch <- kmeansruns(pmatrix, krange = 1:10, criterion = "ch")
clustering.ch$bestk
[1] 2
clustering.asw <- kmeansruns(pmatrix, krange = 1:10, criterion = "asw")
clustering.asw$bestk
[1] 2

      Running kmeansruns for \(k\) range from 1 to 10 have given us the best \(k\) value of 2 for both criterion. Alternatively, we can plot the values for the two criteria across the krange of 1 to 10 to have a better understanding.

critframe <- data.frame(k = 1:10, ch = scale(clustering.ch$crit),
                        asw = scale(clustering.asw$crit))
critframe <- melt(critframe, id.vars = c("k"), variable.name = "measure", value.name = "score")
ggplot(critframe, aes(x = k, y = score, colour = measure)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = measure)) + 
  geom_line(aes(linetype = measure)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:10, labels = 1:10) +
  theme_bw()

      Obviously, the elbow of both criterion is at \(k=2\). From the plot, another possible number of clusters could be \(k=8\).

      Now, let’s carry out the stability assessment one more time for k-means clustering. Again, with the function clusterboot with kmeansCBI method, we can extract the stability numbers from bootmean component and the number of times the clusters were dissolved from bootbrd component.

      The stability number for both cluster 1 and 2 are very high in this case (greater than 0.85), which indicates high stability in both clusters. Hence, these two clusters we found using the k-means clustering method are very likely to be the real clusters. Comparing with the results we obtained from Hierarchical clustering method, clusters based on k-means clustering have a considerably higher stability values. Hence, K-means clustering performs better in finding enrolment patterns in the National Enrollment data.
